                                STORAGE
                                =======
  Make "gadgetdisk" available to target beforehand by...
$ dd if=/dev/zero of=gadgetdisk bs=512 count=4096

MSDOS
$ mkfs.msdos -n "GadgetDisk" -S 512 gadgetdisk 2048

EXT2
$ mkfs -t ext2 -m 0 gadgetdisk 2048

Target
******
insmod s3c2440_udc.ko
insmod g_file_storage.ko file=gadgetdisk removable=1

Connect the USB-CABLE
*********************

Host
****
Windows :- Use it as such

Linux :-
MSDOS
$ mount -t msdos -o loop /dev/sda ./host_mount_dir
EXT2
$ mount -t ext2 -o loop /dev/sda ./host_mount_dir

Target
******
EXT2
$ mount -t ext2 -o loop gadgetdisk ./target_mount_dir
MSDOS
$ mount -t msdos -o loop gadgetdisk ./target_mount_dir
======================================================================

                                SERIAL
                                ======
Target
******
in make menuconfig select 'PPP' under "networking options"

insmod s3c2440_udc.ko
insmod g_serial.ko use_acm=0	(use_acm=1 for windows)
mknod /dev/ttygser c 127 0

Connect the USB-CABLE
*********************

Host
****
modprobe usbserial vendor=0x0525 product=0xa4a6

Target
******
pppd -detach passive noauth nocrtscts 192.168.2.2:192.168.2.1 /dev/ttygser 115200 &

Host
****
pppd -detach passive noauth nocrtscts 192.168.2.1:192.168.2.2 /dev/ttyUSB0 115200 &

======================================================================

                                Ethernet
                                ********
Target
******
For Windows "RNDIS" shud be builtin the target kernel.
For Linux "RNDIS" must be unchecked, it wud take "CDC-Ethernet"

CONNECT THE USB-CABLE
*********************

Target
******
	$ ifconfig usb0 1.2.3.3
	$ ping 1.2.3.4

Host
****
Windows :- Check the "Network Connections" for a new connection

Linux :- 
	$ ifconfig -a	; shud show an extra interface like "eth1"
	$ ifconfig eth1 1.2.3.4
	$ ping 1.2.3.3
